<div id="sorting-bias-in-endogenous-groups" class="section level4">
<h4>Sorting bias in endogenous groups</h4>
<p>Ever worked with grouped data where group membership wasn’t random? Did you correct for endogeneous matching? Here’s why you should.<!--more--></p>
<p>Eh, you already know the answer? Then check out a simple correction method in <a href="https://ideas.repec.org/p/cam/camdae/1521.html"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015a)</span></a> and the <a href="http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/matchingMarkets/matchingMarkets.pdf">documentation</a> and <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/matchingMarkets/vignettes/matching.pdf">vignette</a> <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/matchingMarkets/vignettes/matching.pdf"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015b)</span></a> to R package <a href="http://cran.r-project.org/package=matchingMarkets"><code>matchingMarkets</code></a> <a href="http://cran.r-project.org/package=matchingMarkets"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015c)</span></a>.</p>
<p>Still curious? So here’s why: The figure below plots group outcomes (<span class="math">\(R_{ij}\)</span>) against characteristics (<span class="math">\(X_{ij}\)</span>) for all feasible partitions of 4 agents into groups of two (<span class="math">\(AB\)</span>-<span class="math">\(CD\)</span>, <span class="math">\(AC\)</span>-<span class="math">\(BD\)</span>, <span class="math">\(AD\)</span>-<span class="math">\(BD\)</span>). Underlying this example is a simple linear model where the group characteristic has no effect on outcomes, and thus <span class="math">\(\beta=0\)</span> (black line). If groups are assigned at random, then all 3 partitions are equiprobable and the average slope estimate is zero. If, however, group formation is endogenous, then regression coefficients will generally be biased (red line). <!--In the example, the two agents $A$ and $B$ with better observable and unobservable characteristics form a group.--></p>
<p>Read on for the algebra and R code behind the linear model in this example.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Drawing" style="width: 400px;" /></p>
</div>
<div id="a-simple-model-of-group-diversity" class="section level4">
<h4>A simple model of group diversity</h4>
<p>Let’s start with a simple model where agent <span class="math">\(i\)</span>’s valuation over agent <span class="math">\(j\)</span> is symmetric, that is <span class="math">\(u_{i,j}=u_{j,i}\)</span>. The additive valuation of group <span class="math">\(G\)</span> is then given by the sum over all pairwise valuations</p>
<p><span class="math">\(V_G = \sum_{i\in G} \sum_{j\in G\backslash i} u_{i,j}\)</span>.</p>
<p>Let group valuation <span class="math">\(V_G\)</span> and group outcome <span class="math">\(R_G\)</span> dependent on a group’s diversity <span class="math">\(X\)</span> and some error term. In a population with two types, group diversity can be thought of as the probability of two group members being of the same type. Let’s further assume that everybody prefers to work with members of their own type (<span class="math">\(\alpha=+1\)</span>) but diversified teams are more successful (<span class="math">\(\beta=-1\)</span>).</p>
<p><span class="math">\(V_G = \alpha\cdot X_G + \eta_G\)</span></p>
<p><span class="math">\(R_G = \beta\cdot X_G + \delta\eta_G + \xi_G\)</span> <!--$D = 1$ if $V$ satisfies the equilibrium condition$, 0 otherwise.--></p>
<p>Here, <span class="math">\(\eta_G\)</span> is a group’s unobserved group valuation, which also affects the outcome equation for <span class="math">\(\delta \neq 0\)</span>. Let <span class="math">\(\eta\)</span> capture group members’ individual abilities, which have a positive effect <span class="math">\(\delta = 0.5\)</span> on outcomes. <!--with $\varepsilon_G = \delta\eta_G + \xi_G$--> Finally, the error term <span class="math">\(\zeta_G\)</span> contains random shocks that affect group outcomes but are unknown at group formation.</p>
<p>The endogeneity problem kicks in whenever (i) groups are not formed at random and thus <span class="math">\(cov(X_G, \eta_G)\neq 0\)</span> and (ii) unobserved group characteristics affect group outcomes, <span class="math">\(\delta \neq 0\)</span>. It is resolved when we can control for the unobservable <span class="math">\(\eta\)</span> in the outcome equation.</p>
</div>
<div id="an-example-using-simulated-data" class="section level4">
<h4>An example using simulated data</h4>
<p>To illustrate, let us simulate the bias from endogenous group formation and consider the solution implemented in the <code>matchingMarkets</code> package. I proceed in three steps: generation of individual-level data, transformation to group-level variables and outcomes and, finally, comparison of OLS and the correction method presented in <a href="https://ideas.repec.org/p/cam/camdae/1521.html"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015a)</span></a>.</p>
<div id="individual-level-data" class="section level5">
<h5>Individual-level data</h5>
<p>The <code>stabsim</code> function simulates individual-level, independent variables. The code below generates data for <code>m=1,000</code> markets with <code>gpm=2</code> groups per market and group size <code>ind=5</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>## Simulate individual-level, independent variables
library(matchingMarkets)
idata &lt;- stabsim(m=1000, ind=5, seed=123, gpm=2)
head(idata)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   m.id g.id wst  R
## 1    1    1   0 NA
## 2    1    1   1 NA
## 3    1    1   0 NA
## 4    1    1   1 NA
## 5    1    1   1 NA
## 6    1    2   0 NA</code></pre>
<p>The resulting data contains market and group identifiers <code>m.id</code> and <code>g.id</code> and the independent variable <code>wst</code><span class="math">\(\sim\)</span> B(1,0.5). The dependent variable <code>R</code> depends on the error terms and is still undefined at this stage.</p>
</div>
<div id="group-level-data" class="section level5">
<h5>Group-level data</h5>
<p>Next we apply the function <code>stabit</code> that serves three purposes:</p>
<ul>
<li>First, it specifies the list of variables to be included in <code>selection</code> and <code>outcome</code> equations and generates group-level variables based on group members’ individual characteristics. For example, the operation <code>ieq=&quot;wst&quot;</code> produces the probability that two randomly drawn group members have the same value of <code>wst</code>.</li>
<li>Second, if <code>simulation=&quot;NTU&quot;</code>, it draws standard normal, group-level unobservables <code>eta</code> and <code>xi</code> to enter selection and outcome equation and selects equilibrium groups based on the group formation game with non-transferable utility, assuming pairwise aligned preferences as in <a href="https://ideas.repec.org/p/cam/camdae/1521.html"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015a)</span></a>. In the case of two groups per market, this selection rule results in one dominant group with the maximum group valuation and one group comprised of the residual agents.</li>
<li>Third, the argument <code>method=&quot;model.frame&quot;</code> specifies that only the group-level model matrices be generated. Other options are estimators using <code>&quot;NTU&quot;</code> for selection correction using non-transferable utility matching as selection rule or <code>&quot;outcome&quot;</code> for estimation of the outcome equation only.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>## Simulate group-level variables (takes a minute to complete...)
mdata &lt;- stabit(x=idata, simulation=&quot;NTU&quot;, method=&quot;model.frame&quot;,
                selection = list(ieq=&quot;wst&quot;), 
                outcome   = list(ieq=&quot;wst&quot;))$model.frame</code></pre>
<p>The resulting object <code>mdata</code> is a list containing data for selection and outcome equations in <code>SEL</code> and <code>OUT</code>, respectively. <code>SEL</code> contains 252,000 rows, one for each of <span class="math">\({5 \choose 10}\)</span> = 252 feasible group in each of the 1,000 markets. A group’s valuation is given by <code>V = +1*wst.ieq + eta</code>. The variable <code>D</code> indicates which groups are observed in equilibrium <code>D=1</code> and which are not <code>D=0</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>head(mdata$SEL, 4)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   m.id g.id wst.ieq D          V        eta
## 1    1    1     0.4 1 2.97145815  2.5714581
## 2    1    2     0.4 1 1.11284232  0.7128423
## 3    1    3     0.4 0 0.05608277 -0.3439172
## 4    1    4     0.6 0 2.19850877  1.5985088</code></pre>
<p>The outcome data in <code>OUT</code> contains 2,000 rows, one for each of 2 equilibrium groups per market. The group outcome is given by <code>R = -1*wst.ieq + epsilon</code> with <code>epsilon := +0.5*eta + xi</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>head(mdata$OUT, 4)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   m.id g.id intercept wst.ieq           R         xi    epsilon
## 1    1    1         1     0.4 -0.78221286 -1.6679419 -0.3822129
## 2    1    2         1     0.4  0.17095999  0.2145388  0.5709600
## 3    2    1         1     0.6 -0.57408090 -1.3165104  0.0259191
## 4    2    2         1     0.6 -0.08277463  1.4414618  0.5172254</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="bias-from-sorting" class="section level5">
<h5>Bias from sorting</h5>
<p>The bias in the slope estimate <span class="math">\(\hat\beta-\beta\)</span> = -0.44 - (-1) = 0.56 is illustrated in the left panel of the figure below.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>## Naive OLS estimation
lm(R ~ wst.ieq, data=mdata$OUT)$coefficients</code></pre>
<pre><code>## (Intercept)     wst.ieq 
##   0.3961386  -0.4372392</code></pre>
<p>The source of this bias is the positive correlation between <code>epsilon</code> and the exogenous variable <code>wst.ieq</code> (see the right panel below).</p>
<pre class="r"><code>## epsilon is correlated with independent variables
summary(lm(epsilon ~ wst.ieq, mdata$OUT))$coefficients</code></pre>
<pre><code>##              Estimate Std. Error  t value     Pr(&gt;|t|)
## (Intercept) 0.3961386 0.08758434 4.522939 6.456494e-06
## wst.ieq     0.5627608 0.15889272 3.541766 4.065683e-04</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
<p>An analytical example and a formal treatement of this bias is available in <a href="https://ideas.repec.org/p/cam/camdae/1521.html"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015a)</span></a>. We know that <code>epsilon = 0.5*eta + xi</code>. Thus, conditional on <code>eta</code>, the unobservables in the outcome equation are independent of the exogenous variables (because <code>xi</code> does not enter the selection equation).</p>
<pre class="r"><code>## xi is uncorrelated with independent variables
summary(lm(xi ~ wst.ieq, mdata$OUT))$coefficients</code></pre>
<pre><code>##                Estimate Std. Error    t value  Pr(&gt;|t|)
## (Intercept) -0.03837509 0.06827652 -0.5620540 0.5741423
## wst.ieq      0.04147217 0.12386508  0.3348173 0.7377980</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="correction-of-sorting-bias" class="section level5">
<h5>Correction of sorting bias</h5>
<p>The selection problem is resolved when the residual from the selection equation <code>eta</code> is controlled for in the outcome equation.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>## 1st stage: obtain fitted value for eta
lm.sel &lt;- lm(V ~ -1 + wst.ieq, data=mdata$SEL); lm.sel$coefficients</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  wst.ieq 
## 1.004501</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>eta &lt;- lm.sel$resid[mdata$SEL$D==1]
## 2nd stage: control for eta
lm(R ~ wst.ieq + eta, data=mdata$OUT)$coefficients</code></pre>
<pre><code>## (Intercept)     wst.ieq         eta 
## -0.03858257 -0.96578534  0.50366230</code></pre>
<p>The figure below plots the bias from sorting against the independent variable, for the naive OLS and the selection-correction from the structural model.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
<p>In most real-world applications, however, the match valuations <code>V</code> are unobserved. The solution is to estimate the selection equation by imposing equilibrium bounds, as derived in <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/matchingMarkets/vignettes/matching.pdf"><span class="citation">(Klein 2015b)</span></a>.</p>
</div>
</div>
